window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"The excretory product in protozoans is","images":[],"options":{"A":"amino acids","B":"uric acids","C":"ammonia","D":"urea"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Protozoans are simple, single-celled organisms. They excrete waste products directly into their environment. The primary waste product of protein metabolism in these organisms is ammonia. Ammonia is a toxic compound, but because protozoans live in aquatic environments, they can easily dilute and get rid of this waste product.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"Which of the following is a living organism?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Muscle","B":"Nucleus","C":"Yeast","D":"Mitochondria"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A living organism is a complex structure of interdependent and subordinate elements whose relations and properties are largely determined by their function in the whole. This includes the capacity for growth, reproduction, functional activity, and continual change preceding death. Among the options, Yeast is a living organism. It is a type of fungus that can grow on the surface of foods and drinks, and in the soil, on plants, and in the air because they are tiny, single-celled organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"Which of the following organisms is the most specialized?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Paramecium","B":"Amoeba","C":"Spirogyra","D":"Rhizopus"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Paramecium is a highly specialized protozoan, with features such as:    - A fixed body shape  - A complex oral groove for food capture  - A specialized system of cilia for movement and sensing  - A well-developed contractile vacuole for osmoregulation    In contrast, the other options are less specialized:    - Amoeba is a generalist, with a flexible body shape and a simple structure.  - Spirogyra is a simple, multicellular alga with a basic filamentous structure.  - Rhizopus is a fungus with a relatively simple, multicellular structure.    Specialization in organisms often involves the development of unique features that allow them to thrive in specific environments or ecological niches. Paramecium's specialized features enable it to excel in its aquatic environment, making it the most specialized among the options.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"Active transport can be defined as the movement of","images":[],"options":{"A":"substances from a regions of high concentration to a region of low concentration","B":"substances from a region of low concentration to a region of high concentration to a across a living cell membrane","C":"substances across a living cell membrane using energy from the cell.","D":"movement of molecules in a medium"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Active transport is a process that moves molecules into cells even though they are moving against a concentration gradient. This process requires energy because it is moving substances from an area of lower concentration to an area of higher concentration. This is the opposite of passive transport, which uses no energy because substances move from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Which of the following cell inclusion can destroy other cell organelles?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Centriole","B":"Ribosome","C":"Lysosome","D":"Mitochondrion"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Lysosomes are small round sacs that contain digestive enzymes which break down structures and substances. They usually help in the removal of dead cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : THE CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"In which of the following yam tissues will osmosis occur?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Boiled and peeled","B":"Raw and peeled","C":"Boiled and unpeeled","D":"Roasted and peeled"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Osmosis is the process by which water molecules move from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration through a semi-permeable membrane. In the context of the question, osmosis can only occur in a yam tissue that has not been subjected to heat (boiling or roasting) and has its skin (peel) removed. This is because heat denatures the cell membrane making it impermeable to water, and the peel also acts as a barrier to water movement. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Raw and peeled'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL THEORY","question":"The line XZ in the diagram below represents an actual distance of 10.0cm and the length of the diagram is 5.0cm. What  is the magnification of the diagram?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"x 0.2","B":"x 0.5","C":"x 2.0","D":"x 50.0"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Magnification = Image Length (distance) \u00f7 object length (distance)    M = 5cm \u00f7 10cm; M = 0.5","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"The following events occur during mitosis in a cell.    I. Chromatids separate;    II. Chromosomes becomes visible;    III. Chromosomes align at the equator;   IV. Cytoplasm divides (Cytokinesis)   The correct sequence of the events is","images":[],"options":{"A":"III, II, IV, I","B":"II, III, I, IV","C":"II, I, III, IV","D":"II, IV, I, III"},"answer":"B","explanation":"During mitosis, 1. The chromosomes becomes conspicuous (visible)    2. The nuclear membrane disappears: a spindle forms, the chromosomes line up across the  middle of the cell and become attached to the spindle fibres at the centromeres.    3. The 'sister' chromatids are pulled apart to opposite ends (poles) of the cells as the spindle fibres contrast.    4. The cell divides into two daughter cells (cytokinesis).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Which of the following statements about asexual reproduction is correct? It","images":[],"options":{"A":"may involves two parent but the offsprings is always identical to one parent","B":"always involves two parent and the offspring are  not genetically identical to the parent","C":"always involves one parent and the offspring are genetically identical to the parent","D":"involves two parents but the offspring is not genetically identical to any of the parents"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Asexual reproduction is a type of reproduction where only one parent is involved and the offspring are genetically identical to the parent. This is because the offspring are produced by a single parent without the involvement of sperm and egg. This leads to offspring that are genetically identical to the parent, also known as clones. Therefore, option 3 is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a mammalian bone.     Use it to answer this question    The bone illustrated above is the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"femur","B":"humerus","C":"radius","D":"ulna"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The femur, or thigh bone, is the longest and strongest bone in the human body. It extends from the hip to the knee and plays a crucial role in supporting the body's weight and enabling leg movement. Here are some key features of the femur:  1.\tProximal End (Head)  2.\tGreater and Lesser Trochanters  3.\tShaft  4.\tDistal End  The diagram aligns with the structure of the femur.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a mammalian bone.     Use it to answer this question  The function of the part labelled I is to","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"fit into the glenoid cavity of the scapula","B":"fit into the acetabulum of the pelvic girdle","C":"support the lower arm","D":"prevent the arm from bending backwards"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The proximal end of the femur fits into the acetabulum. Specifically, the rounded head of the femur articulates with the acetabulum of the pelvis to form the hip joint, which is a ball-and-socket joint that allows for a wide range of motion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following processes is not a function of the mammalian skin?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Regulation of body temperature","B":"Reception of external stimuli","C":"Excretion","D":"Gaseous exchange"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The mammalian skin is not involved in gaseous exchange. Gaseous exchange, which involves the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide, primarily takes place in the lungs in mammals. The skin, however, is involved in the regulation of body temperature, reception of external stimuli, and excretion through sweat. Therefore, option 4 is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The legs of an accident victim with a fractured vertebral column and injured spinal cord could not be raised because","images":[],"options":{"A":"impulses from receptors in the legs cannot travel to the brain","B":"impulses from the brain cannot travel to the legs","C":"chemical substances will be released at synapses in the central nervous system","D":"reflex actions cannot take place in the legs"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The spinal cord is a major pathway for information flowing back and forth between the brain and the skin, muscles, and visceral organs. It is also a center for coordinating many reflexes. If the spinal cord is injured, the flow of information (impulses) from the brain to the legs is disrupted, hence the legs cannot be raised.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Which of the following conditions in flowering plants enhance self pollination?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Cleistogamy","B":"Heterostyly","C":"Protandry","D":"Protogyny"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Cleistogamy is a condition in flowering plants where flowers remain closed and self-pollinate without opening. This ensures that self-pollination occurs, enhancing the likelihood of self-fertilization.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of the left side of the human cerebrum.      The part labelled X controls","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"general memory","B":"speech","C":"sight","D":"respiratory functions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Based on the location marked \"X\" in the diagram, it appears to be pointing to the posterior part of the left cerebral hemisphere, which is typically associated with the occipital lobe.    The occipital lobe is primarily responsible for processing visual information. Therefore, the correct answer should be: Sight    The part labeled \"X\" is located in the occipital lobe, which is responsible for visual processing. This lobe interprets visual stimuli and information from the eyes. Hence, it is associated with sight.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Use the diagram below to answer this question.    The diagram above is an illustration of","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"normal sight","B":"short sightedness","C":"correction of long sightedness","D":"correction of short sightedness"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The diagram on the Left Hand Side indicates the defect of long sightedness and that of the Right Hand Side is the correction of the defect.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"The inability to maintain proper balance of the body in humans may be due to a defect in the","images":[],"options":{"A":"cochlea","B":"eustachian tube","C":"semi-circular canals","D":"oval window"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The semi-circular canals in the inner ear are responsible for maintaining balance in the human body. They are filled with a fluid that moves when your head changes position, and they have sensory hair cells that send signals to the brain about the body's motion and orientation in space.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"The following substances pass into the blood of the foetus from the mother's blood via the placenta except","images":[],"options":{"A":"carbon dioxide","B":"glucose","C":"viruses","D":"antibodies"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The placenta allows the exchange of nutrients, gases, and waste products between the mother and the fetus. However, it does not allow the passage of most harmful substances, such as carbon dioxide. The fetus gets rid of carbon dioxide by sending it back through the placenta to the mother's bloodstream, which then removes it through the mother's lungs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"An inferior ovary of a flower is situated","images":[],"options":{"A":"below the floral parts","B":"above the floral parts","C":"at the same level with all the floral parts","D":"at the centre of the floral parts"},"answer":"A","explanation":"An inferior ovary is a term used in botany to describe the position of the ovary of a flower in relation to the other parts of the flower. When the ovary is said to be inferior, it means it is situated below the other floral parts. This is in contrast to a superior ovary, which is situated above the other floral parts.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Older parts of plants roots do not normally absorb water because","images":[],"options":{"A":"they lack xylem","B":"they have small surface area","C":"the phloem is dead","D":"they lack root hairs"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Older parts of plant roots do not normally absorb water because they lack root hairs. Root hairs are tiny hair-like extensions that increase the surface area of the root allowing it to absorbs more water and nutrients from the soil. As the root ages, these root hairs die off, reducing the root's ability to absorb water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The amount of starch in a germinating seed decreases because the starch is used up","images":[],"options":{"A":"for respiration and building up of cells","B":"to build cellulose cell wall","C":"to develop meristematic tissues","D":"for the production of enzymes"},"answer":"A","explanation":"During germination, the stored starch in a seed is broken down into simpler sugars by enzymes. These sugars are then used for respiration to provide energy for the growing seedling and for building up of cells. Respiration is a metabolic process that converts stored energy into usable energy. The building up of cells is part of growth and development of the seedling.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"The purpose of treating poor soil with lime is to increase the quantity of","images":[],"options":{"A":"nitrogen","B":"phosphorus","C":"calcium","D":"sulphur"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The purpose of treating poor soil with lime (calcium carbonate) is to increase the quantity of calcium in the soil. Lime is used to neutralize the acidity of soil and improve its structure. Calcium is an essential nutrient for plant growth. It is involved in cell wall structure, cell division, and is a co-factor for some enzymes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"A meal consisting of yam and a lot of vegetables is not balanced because it does not contain","images":[],"options":{"A":"carbohydrates","B":"protein","C":"vitamins","D":"mineral"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A balanced diet is one that gives your body the nutrients it needs to function correctly. It must contain the right amount of all the different types of nutrients, including carbohydrates, proteins, vitamins, and minerals. In the given question, the meal consists of yam and a lot of vegetables. Yam is a good source of carbohydrates and vegetables are rich in vitamins and minerals. However, this meal lacks protein, which is essential for growth and repair in the body. Therefore, the meal is not balanced because it does not contain protein.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PROPERTIES AND FUNCTIONS OF THE LIVING CELL","question":"In a Biuret, some protein was mixed with Sodium Hydroxide solution. Which of the following chemicals should be added to the mixture for a positive result?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Mercurous Nitrate","B":"Copper Sulphate","C":"Sodium Carbonate","D":"Silver Nitrate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Biuret test is a chemical test used for detecting the presence of peptide bonds. In the presence of peptides, a copper(II) ion forms violet-colored coordination complexes in an alkaline solution. In this test, Sodium Hydroxide (NaOH) is used to make the solution alkaline. Then, Copper Sulphate (CuSO4) is added. If protein is present, the solution will turn purple. Therefore, Copper Sulphate should be added to the mixture for a positive result.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"A characteristic feature of plant parasites is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"possession of holdfast","B":"possession of rhizoids","C":"development of hanging roots","D":"development of haustoria"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A characteristic feature of plant parasites is the development of haustoria. Haustoria are specialized structures that the parasitic plant uses to penetrate the host plant's tissue and draw nutrients from it. This is not to be confused with holdfasts, which are root-like structures that some plants use to anchor themselves to a surface, or rhizoids, which are similar but found in non-vascular plants like mosses and liverworts. Hanging roots are not a characteristic feature of parasitic plants.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HIS HEALTH.","question":"The part of a leguminous plant where bacteria like Azotobacter can be found is","images":[],"options":{"A":"at the nodes of the stem","B":"at the internodes","C":"in the root nodules","D":"in the spongy mesophyll"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Bacteria like Azotobacter can be found in the root nodules of leguminous plants. These bacteria are able to fix atmospheric nitrogen into a form that the plant can use. This symbiotic relationship benefits the plant by providing it with a source of nitrogen, and benefits the bacteria by providing them with a protected environment and nutrients from the plant. The nodes of the stem, internodes, and spongy mesophyll are not typically where these bacteria are found.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The following adaptations are associated with the flight of birds except","images":[],"options":{"A":"reduced body weight","B":"streamlined shape","C":"presence of powerful muscles","D":"clawed digits"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The adaptations associated with the flight of birds include reduced body weight, streamlined shape, and the presence of powerful muscles. These adaptations help birds to fly efficiently. Reduced body weight makes it easier for birds to lift off the ground. A streamlined shape reduces air resistance, making flight more efficient. Powerful muscles, particularly in the wings, provide the force needed for flight. However, clawed digits are not an adaptation for flight. They are used for perching, grasping prey, or for defense, but they do not aid in the act of flying.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"The following habitats can be found in West Africa  except","images":[],"options":{"A":"magrove swamp","B":"sahel savanna","C":"savanna grassland","D":"temperate grassland"},"answer":"D","explanation":"They can be found in Temperate pacific grasslands of North America, the Pampas of Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay, calcareous downland, and the steppes of Europe.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"The difference between a community and population is","images":[],"options":{"A":"a community is made up of organisms of the same species while a population is made up of organisms of different species","B":"a community is made up of populations of living organisms while a population is made up of organisms of the same species","C":"an ecological niche does not exist in the community but it does in a population","D":"a community attracts competition but a population does not"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A community is a group of populations of different species living in the same geographical area, and potentially interacting with each other. A population, on the other hand, is a group of individuals of the same species living in the same geographical area. Therefore, a community is made up of populations of living organisms while a population is made up of organisms of the same species.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : WATER CYCLE","question":"Which of the following statements about the circulation of water in nature is not correct? Water","images":[],"options":{"A":"constantly evaporates from seas, rivers, lakes and soil","B":"vapour rises, cools, condenses and precipitates as rain and dew.","C":"removed from oceans is permanently lost","D":"is lost in plants by transpiration and decay"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Water removed from oceans vaporizes to the cloud, this water vapour condenses and precipitation occurs in form of rain, snow and hail to return the removed water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The diagram below illustrates an ecological instrument.      Use it to answer this question    The instrument is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"an anemometer","B":"a hygrometer","C":"a barometer","D":"a wind vane"},"answer":"D","explanation":"This is the structure of the wind-vane. The cardinal points help to identify the direction of the wind.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The diagram below illustrates an ecological instrument.      Use it to answer this question   The instrument is used to measure the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"direction of wind","B":"speed of wind","C":"air pressure in a habitat","D":"turbidity of water"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Wind-vane is used to indicate the direction of wind.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"The following organisms are consumers except","images":[],"options":{"A":"earthworm","B":"Spirogyra","C":"Bacteria","D":"Rhizopus"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Spirogyra is a type of green algae that is photosynthetic. Photosynthetic organisms are producers, not consumers. They produce their own food by converting sunlight, carbon dioxide, and water into glucose and oxygen. Consumers, on the other hand, are organisms that cannot produce their own food and must consume other organisms for energy. Therefore, Spirogyra is not a consumer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : POLLUTION OF THE ATMOSPHERE","question":"Use the substances listed below to answer this question    I. Fertilizer  II. Insecticides  III. Sewage  IV. Crude oil   V. Sulphur dioxide    The atmosphere can be polluted by","images":[],"options":{"A":"I only","B":"III only","C":"IV only","D":"II and V only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Atmospheric pollution can be caused by a variety of substances, including insecticides and sulphur dioxide. Insecticides can be carried into the atmosphere when they are sprayed, and they can harm non-target organisms and disrupt ecosystems. Sulphur dioxide is a gas that is released by industrial processes, such as the burning of fossil fuels. It can react with water, oxygen, and other chemicals in the atmosphere to form acid rain, which can harm both terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems. Therefore, both insecticides (II) and sulphur dioxide (V) can pollute the atmosphere.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : POLLUTION OF THE ATMOSPHERE","question":"Use the substances listed below to answer this question    I. Fertilizer  II. Insecticides  III. Sewage  IV. Crude oil   V. Sulphur dioxide  Which of the substance constitute domestic waste?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I only","B":"III only","C":"IV only","D":"II and V only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Domestic waste refers to waste that is generated as a result of household activities. It includes things like food scraps, paper, glass, bottles, etc. In the given options, sewage (III) is a type of domestic waste. Fertilizer (I) and Insecticides (II) are agricultural wastes, Crude oil (IV) is an industrial waste and Sulphur dioxide (V) is a type of air pollution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : POLLUTION OF THE ATMOSPHERE","question":"The table below shows the oxygen level, number of green plants and fish in rivers flowing through four towns.   Which of the towns is likely to be discharging untreated sewage in their river?   TownOxygen LevelGreen PlantsFishAHighFewManyBLowManyManyCHighFewFewDLowManyFew","images":[],"options":{"A":"High, Few, Many","B":"Low, Many, Many","C":"High, Few, Few","D":"Low, Many, Few"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The town that is likely discharging untreated sewage into their river would be the one with low oxygen levels, many green plants, and few fish. This is because untreated sewage can lead to an increase in nutrients in the water, which can cause an overgrowth of plants and algae (eutrophication). This overgrowth can deplete the water's oxygen, making it hard for fish and other aquatic life to survive. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Low, Many, Few' which corresponds to town D in the table.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"Which of the following natural resources is non-renewable?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Water","B":"Coal","C":"Forest","D":"Air"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Non-renewable resources are resources that cannot be replenished within a short period of time. Coal is a non-renewable resource because it takes millions of years to form from the remains of plants and animals. Water, forest, and air are renewable resources because they can be replenished naturally in a short period of time.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT","question":"Which of the following statements is not a reason for banning bush burning? It","images":[],"options":{"A":"allows  for quick regrowth of grasses","B":"kills soil micro-organisms","C":"Leaves the soil bare of vegetation","D":"burns off organic soil nutrients"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Bush burning is a practice that involves setting fire to vegetation in a particular area. While it can allow for quick regrowth of grasses, it is generally discouraged because it can lead to soil degradation, loss of biodiversity, and other environmental problems. Therefore, the statement that bush burning allows for quick regrowth of grasses is not a reason for banning it. On the other hand, killing soil micro-organisms, leaving the soil bare of vegetation, and burning off organic soil nutrients are all negative impacts of bush burning and valid reasons for banning it.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Which of the statements below explains why fertilizers are added to soils?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Increasing the humus content of the soil.","B":"Improving the water-retaining property of the soil","C":"Increasing the nutrient level of the soil","D":"Preventing soil erosion"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fertilizers are added to soils primarily to increase the nutrient level of the soil. They provide essential nutrients like nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium that plants need for growth. The other options, such as increasing the humus content, improving water-retaining property, and preventing soil erosion, are not the primary reasons for adding fertilizers.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Characteristic that exhibit continuous variation are generally controlled by","images":[],"options":{"A":"a single gene","B":"recessive genes","C":"epistatic  interactions","D":"multiple genes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Characteristics that exhibit continuous variation are generally controlled by multiple genes. This is known as polygenic inheritance, where multiple genes contribute to a single trait. A single gene or recessive genes do not control continuous variation. Epistatic interactions refer to the interaction of different genes, not the number of genes controlling a trait.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Differences in characteristics that exist among individual of the same species is referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"genetics","B":"dominance","C":"hybrid","D":"variation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The differences in characteristics that exist among individuals of the same species is referred to as variation. Variation can be due to genetic differences, environmental factors, or a combination of both. It is a fundamental aspect of life on Earth and is a driving force behind evolution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following traits is not a morphological variation in humans?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Ability to taste PTC","B":"Colour","C":"Fingerprint","D":"Size"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Morphological variations refer to physical differences in form and structure among individuals of the same species. The ability to taste PTC (phenylthiocarbamide) is a genetic trait, not a morphological one. It is determined by the presence or absence of certain alleles (versions of a gene). On the other hand, color, fingerprint, and size are all examples of morphological variations.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Which of the following statements about chromosome is correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"All the chromosomes of a species are the same in shape","B":"The number present in a species is constant","C":"They are nearly arranged in the cytoplasm","D":"They bear ribosomes on their outer membranes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Chromosomes are thread-like structures located inside the nucleus of animal and plant cells. Each chromosome is made of protein and a single molecule of deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA). The number of chromosomes is a characteristic that is constant in the cells of individuals of the same species. For example, humans have 46 chromosomes in each cell, while dogs have 78. The other options are incorrect because chromosomes are not the same in shape, they are not arranged in the cytoplasm, and they do not bear ribosomes on their outer membranes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"A small stem from a hibiscus plant was placed in nutrient medium and it developed into a new plant.   The new plant was reproduced","images":[],"options":{"A":"asexually with a different genotype from the parent plant","B":"sexually with a different genotype from the parent plant","C":"asexually with the same genotype as the parent plant","D":"sexually with the same genotype as the parent plant"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The process described in the question is known as plant tissue culture, which is a form of asexual reproduction. In this process, a small piece of plant tissue (the stem in this case) is taken and placed in a nutrient medium where it develops into a new plant. Because this is a form of asexual reproduction, the new plant will have the same genetic makeup (genotype) as the parent plant. The other options are incorrect because the new plant is not produced sexually, and it does not have a different genotype from the parent plant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"The F1 generation of a cross between a red cock and a white hen were all red because the gene for the","images":[],"options":{"A":"white colour did not segregate","B":"red colour was dominant","C":"white colour was dominant","D":"red colour was recessive"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The organisms (individual) in the F1 generation are red because of the dominance of the red colour.    The organism in the F1 generation are red because the gene for the red colour as dominant","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following disease can be inherited?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Pneumonia","B":"AIDS","C":"Sickle cell anaemia","D":"Goitre"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Sickle cell anaemia is a genetic disease that can be inherited. It is caused by a mutation in the gene that tells your body to make the red, iron-rich compound that gives blood its red color (hemoglobin). Pneumonia and AIDS are infectious diseases caused by bacteria and virus respectively, and Goitre is a condition that results from the enlargement of the thyroid gland, which is not inherited.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"In dihybrid inheritance, Mendel considered","images":[],"options":{"A":"a pair of contrasting characters","B":"two pairs of contrasting characters","C":"three pairs of contrasting characters","D":"four pairs of contrasting characters"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In dihybrid inheritance, Mendel considered two pairs of contrasting characters. Dihybrid inheritance is a term used in genetics to describe the simultaneous inheritance of two distinct traits. It was first discovered by Gregor Mendel who conducted experiments on pea plants. He studied two traits at a time, hence the term 'dihybrid'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The main reason for nuptial flight in termites is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"escape unfavourable conditions","B":"search for food","C":"form new colonies","D":"communicate with one another"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The main reason for nuptial flight in termites is to form new colonies. Nuptial flight is an important phase in the reproduction of most ant, termite, and some bee species. During the flight, virgin queens mate and then land to start a new colony, or, in the case of honey bees, to continue the succession of an existing hived colony.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Which of the following organisms is not a social insect?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Termites","B":"Ants","C":"Grasshoppers","D":"Bees"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Social insects are those that live in colonies or have a division of labor. Termites, ants, and bees are all examples of social insects. Grasshoppers, on the other hand, are not social insects. They are solitary insects that do not live in colonies or have a division of labor.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2014>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2014","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Lamarck's theory of evolution is based on the fact that","images":[],"options":{"A":"organisms acquire genes from their parents","B":"organisms pass on acquired characters to their offspring","C":"characteristics of organisms are determined by the creator","D":"characteristics of organisms are not the sum of their parents' characters."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Lamarck's theory of evolution, also known as Lamarckism, proposes that an organism can change during its lifetime in response to its environment, and those changes are inheritable. This means that an organism can pass on characteristics that it has acquired during its lifetime to its offspring. Therefore, the statement 'organisms pass on acquired characters to their offspring' is the correct representation of Lamarck's theory of evolution.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"}];